    <h2>The Breakdown</h2>

    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-card-header">
        <span class="app-type-badge">Everything Tracker</span>
        <h3>MyFitnessPal</h3>
      </div>
      <p>MFP is the most widely used nutrition app in the world for a reason — it does everything. Calories, macros, micros, meal logging, barcode scanning, a database of millions of foods. If you want to track your entire nutritional picture, it's the most capable tool available.</p>
      <p>The problem isn't that it's bad. It's that it's solving a different problem. For a man over 40 whose goal is simply hitting 120–150g of protein per day, MFP introduces a level of friction that tends to kill consistency. Add in the barcode scanner paywall they implemented in 2022, and the free version is considerably less useful than it used to be.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-card-header">
        <span class="app-type-badge">Precision / Clinical</span>
        <h3>Cronometer</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Cronometer is the most precise nutrition tracker available. It goes deeper than MFP — amino acid profiles, micronutrient breakdowns, verified food data. If you're working with a dietitian or managing a specific health condition, this level of detail has real value.</p>
      <p>For most men over 40 with a protein target and a busy life, it's the definition of more data than you need. The interface reflects its precision — there's nothing casual about it. Power tool for a specific user.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="app-card">
      <div class="app-card-header">
        <span class="app-type-badge">Weight Loss / Calorie Focus</span>
        <h3>Lose It</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Lose It is built around one primary idea: eat fewer calories to lose weight. It does that well. The interface is clean, the calorie budget is front and center, and the food logging is straightforward.</p>
      <p>The issue is goal alignment. Muscle preservation after 40 isn't primarily a calorie problem — it's a protein problem. Lose It can show you protein as a secondary metric, but the entire product experience is oriented around deficit and weight loss. If that's your goal, it's a solid choice. If it's not, you'll be swimming against the current every day you use it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="app-card snap-card">
